1
00:00:00,208 --> 00:00:05,916
Interviewer: After you served your time in prison, how did your life change?

2
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:07,708
Is your life the same as before prison?

3
00:00:07,791 --> 00:00:12,000
No, but I’ve started to feel that I’m being watched, and so on

4
00:00:14,875 --> 00:00:21,041
Interviewer: Didn’t you develop a nervous or hysterical condition

5
00:00:21,125 --> 00:00:23,041
After you were released, or any specific mental illness?

6
00:00:23,166 --> 00:00:28,125
No, but I feel my nerves are tense to this day

7
00:00:30,791 --> 00:00:34,125
Interviewer: Is the way you deal with your wife and kids the same as before prison?

8
00:00:34,333 --> 00:00:37,708
I mean your relationship with them, in terms of mindset and behavior?

9
00:00:37,750 --> 00:00:40,291
No, there is none of that

10
00:00:40,625 --> 00:00:42,458
Interviewer: Did they notice any kind of change in you?

11
00:00:42,958 --> 00:00:47,583
Only sometimes I get moments of nervous tension, as soon as I get annoyed by something

12
00:00:47,625 --> 00:00:51,041
Interviewer: Your closest person, your wife—did she tell you that you weren’t like this before?

13
00:00:51,166 --> 00:00:53,333
Yes, I wasn’t like this before, I don’t even have any patience

14
00:00:53,625 --> 00:00:59,458
Now wherever I am, I have no patience, I don’t like to talk much about any topic

15
00:01:00,333 --> 00:01:03,625
Interviewer: Did it happen to you after you were released, that in the morning when you wake up

16
00:01:03,958 --> 00:01:05,625
You wake in the morning and can’t open your eyes?

17
00:01:06,166 --> 00:01:08,708
Afraid that you’re still in prison and you were dreaming you got out?

18
00:01:09,166 --> 00:01:12,708
By God, talking about those things—when I was detained and when I was released

19
00:01:12,791 --> 00:01:14,791
A big problem, and the hardest feeling

20
00:01:15,166 --> 00:01:18,875
When I got home, they hadn’t expected that I would come back
